UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2462
1 A JOINT RESOLUTION designating the Dr. John Dallas Stempel Memorial
2 Highway in Fayette County.
3 WHEREAS, John Dallas Stempel was born on July 26, 1938, in Easton,
4 Pennsylvania, the son of John Emmert and Mary Farmer Stempel; and
5 WHEREAS, John Dallas Stempel attended Princeton University's Woodrow Wilson
6 School, where he won top academic honors. Upon graduation in 1960, he earned a Navy
7 commission through his time in the Princeton NROTC program; and
8 WHEREAS, John Dallas Stempel was assigned to the USS Walton (DE-361),
9 operating out of San Francisco, and in 1961 the ship was ordered to Vietnam to help train
10 the small Vietnamese Navy; and
11 WHEREAS, after his military service was complete, John Dallas Stempel attended
12 the University of California, Berkeley, where he received both an MA and a PhD in
13 Political Science; and
14 WHEREAS, John Dallas Stempel joined the United States Foreign Service in 1965,
15 serving three tours in Africa sandwiched around time in Washington; and
16 WHEREAS, John Dallas Stempel moved to Tehran, Iran, in 1975 to serve as
17 Deputy Chief of the political section and later Chief during the countdown to the 1979
18 Iranian Revolution. In 1981, he published his first scholarly book, Inside the Iranian
19 Revolution, while he was Diplomat-in-Residence at the United States Naval Academy;
20 and
21 WHEREAS, after a 24-year career in the Foreign Service, John Dallas Stempel
22 began a second career as a professor of International Affairs at the Patterson School of
23 Diplomacy and International Commerce at the University of Kentucky; and
24 WHEREAS, in 1993, Dr. Stempel was named Director of the Patterson School.
25 During his directorship, he revised and released a 2nd edition of Inside the Iranian
26 Revolution and wrote Common Sense in Foreign Policy (2008), which he joked would be
27 "a very short book"; and
Page 1 of 2
